To change the focus color for a TextField in Kotlin, you can set the focusedIndicatorColor property. Here&#39;s an example:

       &lt;com.google.android.material.textfield.TextInputLayout
    android:id=&quot;@+id/myTextFieldLayout&quot;
    android:layout_width=&quot;match_parent&quot;
    android:layout_height=&quot;wrap_content&quot;
    app:hint=&quot;My TextField&quot;
    app:focusedIndicatorColor=&quot;@color/my_focus_color&quot;&gt;
    &lt;com.google.android.material.textfield.TextInputEditText
        android:id=&quot;@+id/myTextField&quot;
        android:layout_width=&quot;match_parent&quot;
        android:layout_height=&quot;wrap_content&quot;/&gt;
&lt;/com.google.android.material.textfield.TextInputLayout&gt;

In the above code, we set the focusedIndicatorColor property of the TextInputLayout to a custom color defined in the my_focus_color resource.

Alternatively, you can also set this property programmatically in Kotlin code:

    val myTextFieldLayout = findViewById&lt;TextInputLayout&gt;(R.id.myTextFieldLayout)
myTextFieldLayout.setBoxStrokeColorResource(R.color.my_focus_color)

In the above code, we use the setBoxStrokeColorResource() method to set the focus color to my_focus_color.

Note that the focusedIndicatorColor property was added in Material Components version 1.1.0. If you are using an older version, you can use the setBoxStrokeColor() method instead.

